                    <note type="abstract" xml:id="abstract-en-1901">In hagiography: <persName>Forty Martyrs of Sebaste</persName> were a group of Roman soldiers martyred under <persName>Licinius</persName> who were commemorated collectively not only in the Greek church but widely across late antique Christianity. Their Syriac cult is not only attested by a rich textual tradition but also by numerous churches and monasteries including <placeName>Church of the Forty Martyrs</placeName> in <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/130">Mardin</placeName>, <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/1852">Church of the Forty Martyrs</placeName> in <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/110.html">Karamlish</placeName>, <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/386">Dayro d-Modiq</placeName>, and <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/336">Dayr Ibn Jājī</placeName>.</note>
                    <bibl xml:id="bib1901-1">
